Duduzane Zuma was released on R100 000 bail after making a brief appearance at the Specialised Commercial Crime Court in Johannesburg on Monday Zuma, who was shackled in cuffs, was ordered to hand over his travel documents. He’ll also need to apply for permission if he wishes to travel. His case was postponed to 24 January 2019. Yesterday Zuma’s lawyer, Rudi Krause, confirmed that he would be appearing in court today. City Press reported that he was set to be charged with corruption – apparently in connection with the role he allegedly played in an incident where former deputy finance minister Mcebisi Jonas has said there was an attempt to bribe him at the Guptas’ Saxonwold home in 2015. According to the newspaper, sources from the Hawks had revealed that Zuma would be charged with contravening the Prevention and Combating of Corrupt Activities Act. READ MORE: Duduzane Zuma summoned to court for culpable homicide Zuma has apparently been overseas since February. However, his brother, Vusi Nhlakanipho Zuma, died recently of lupus and Zuma came to attend his funeral. According to City Press, Zuma was seen at the funeral service, held at Rhema Church in Randburg on Saturday. He was briefly detained at the OR Tambo International Airport after landing there on Thursday evening. After his identity was confirmed by Hawks officers, he was released. Furthermore, earlier this month, Zuma received a summons to appear in the Randburg Magistrate’s Court on July 12 on two charges of culpable homicide. The charges related to a car crash in February 2014 during which Zuma rear-ended a taxi after losing control of his Porsche on the Grayston Drive off-ramp on the M1, north of Johannesburg. One woman died instantly and three others were injured. – News24Wire